==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|colloquium||conversation|lang=la}},<ref>{{R:American Heritage 2000}}</ref> from {{term|com-||together, with|lang=la}} (English {{term|com-|lang=en}}) + form of {{term|loquor||speak|lang=la}} (from which English {{term|locution|lang=en}} and other words).<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{enPR|kŏl'ə-kwē}}, {{IPA|/ˈkɒ.lə.kwi/}}, {{SAMPA|/"kQ.le.kwi/}}
* {{audio|Colloquy pronunciation.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|colloquies}}

# A [[conversation]] or [[dialogue]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#* '''1897''', Henry James, ''What Maisie Knew'':
#*: And she repeated the free caress into which her '''colloquies''' with Maisie almost always broke and which made the child feel that ''her'' affection at least was a gage of safety.
# {{obsolete}} A formal [[conference]]. {{defdate|16th-17th c.}}
# {{Christianity}} A church [[court]] held by certain Reformed denominations. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
# A written [[discourse]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
# {{legal}} A discussion during a [[trial]] in which a judge ensures that the [[defendant]] understands what is taking place in the trial and what their rights are.

